'''Alexander Gordon''' (1752-1799) was a renowned Edwardian [[obstetrician]] best known for being the first person to describe the infectious nature of childbirth fever in his paper of 1795 entitled ''Treatise on the Epidemic Puerperal Fever of Aberdeen''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.med-chi.co.uk/heritage/people/alexander-gordon-1752-1799.html#nav|title=Alexander Gordon (1752 - 1799) - Aberdeen Medico-Chirurgical Society|first=Kyle|last=Shearer|website=www.med-chi.co.uk}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.abdn.ac.uk/news/4797/|title=200-year-old medical manuscript given new life - News - The University of Aberdeen|website=www.abdn.ac.uk}}</ref> His remarkable paper gave insights into the contagious nature of puerperal fever more than half a century before Ignaz Semmelweis and before the science of bacteria was known about.<ref>{{cite journal |doi=10.1783/147118910793048548 |pmid=21067645 |title=Dr Alexander Gordon of Aberdeen |journal=Journal of Family Planning and Reproductive Health Care |volume=36 |issue=4 |pages=253 |year=2010 |last1=Smith |first1=Lesley }}</ref> 

Gordon was born in 1752 in [[Strachan, Aberdeenshire|Strachan]], [[Scotland]]. He studied medicine at the [[University of Aberdeen]]'s [[Marischal College]].<ref>{{cite journal |doi=10.1136/fn.78.3.F232 |title=Dr Alexander Gordon (1752-99) and contagious puerperal fever |journal=Archives of Disease in Childhood: Fetal and Neonatal Edition |volume=78 |issue=3 |pages=F232–F233 |year=1998 |last1=Dunn |first1=P. M }}</ref>

